How to Create a Simple Repository Using the GitHub Website
Step 1: Sign in to GitHub
Open your web browser.
Go to GitHub.
Sign in to your GitHub account.
Step 2: Create a New Repository
Click the "+" (Plus) icon in the upper-right corner.
Select New repository from the dropdown menu.
Step 3: Configure the Repository

Fill in the required details:

Repository Name – Enter a unique and descriptive name.
Example: student-management-system
Description (Optional) – Briefly describe the project.
Visibility
Public – Anyone can view the repository.
Private – Only authorized collaborators can access it.
Step 4: Initialize the Repository (Recommended)

You may select the following options:

Add a README file

Creates a README.md file where you can describe your project.

Add .gitignore

Excludes unnecessary files from being tracked by Git.

Choose a License

Defines how others can use your project.
Step 5: Create the Repository
Click the Create repository button.
GitHub will generate your repository and redirect you to its main page.

